  "prompt": "For NSF Fellowship applicants, what is the difference between \"Very Good\" and \"Excellent\"?",
  "response": "For NSF Graduate Research Fellowship Program (GRFP) reviews, the difference between \"Very Good\" and \"Excellent\" can be nuanced:\n\n\"Very Good\" typically indicates:\n- Strong application\n- Solid qualifications\n- Good potential\n- Meets most criteria well\n- Some room for improvement\n\n\"Excellent\" typically indicates:\n- Outstanding application\n- Exceptional qualifications\n- Demonstrated potential for significant research contributions\n- Meets or exceeds all criteria\n- Highly competitive candidate\n- Distinctive achievements or experiences\n- Clear potential to be a future leader in research\n\nThe jump from \"Very Good\" to \"Excellent\" often involves:\n- More impactful research proposals\n- Clearer research vision\n- Stronger letters of recommendation\n- More significant research/academic achievements\n- More compelling personal statements\n- More innovative or promising research ideas\n\nReviewers look for that extra level of distinction that sets an \"Excellent\" application apart from a \"Very Good\" one. This often means showing not just competence, but true potential for transformative research.",
